commText: Prithvi Shaw and Fraser-McGurk are at the crease. Prithvi Shaw is on strike. Warrier will open the attack
Warrier to Prithvi Shaw, 1 run, fullish outswinger outside off, shapes away, Prithvi Shaw guides it nicely with an open face to third man and is off the mark

Warrier to Fraser-McGurk, SIX, this fellow is special. First ball and it's lofted straight down the ground, Sourav Ganguly in the DC dugout is shaking his head and smiling wryly, fullish outside off, Fraser-McGurk holds his shape, lofts and it flies all the way

Warrier to Fraser-McGurk, no run, full on off, hint of away shape and Fraser-McGurk almost spoons the drive straight to the fielder at mid-off, on the bounce, Fraser-McGurk suggests to Prithvi Shaw that it moved away
Warrier to Fraser-McGurk, FOUR, thumped back. Full on off, in the slot, lofted dismissively straight down the ground. Now Warner is smiling wryly, they know this Fraser-McGurk has something in him
Warrier to Fraser-McGurk, leg byes, 1 run, sliding down leg, Fraser-McGurk flicks and misses, off the pads for a legbye
DRS! Gill goes for an LBW review against Prithvi Shaw. Wickets is ump's call.

Warrier to Prithvi Shaw, leg byes, 2 runs, GT don't lose the review. A sharp nipbacker from Warrier, but sliding down, Prithvi Shaw flicks and misses, impact on leg-stump and just clipping leg-stump, the original call was not out
Spencer Johnson, left-arm fast medium, comes into the attack
Spencer Johnson to Fraser-McGurk, wide, starts with a wide down leg, swing though for Spencer Johnson, Fraser-McGurk flicks and misses
Spencer Johnson to Fraser-McGurk, SIX, smashed away. Fraser-McGurk makes room and this is full and just outside off, he carves it away with an open face, flies all the way over deep backward point
Spencer Johnson to Fraser-McGurk, no run, back of a length and dug in on the stumps, Fraser-McGurk makes room to flat-bat, mistimes it to mid-off
Spencer Johnson to Fraser-McGurk, no run, that's the pace you need to bowl at this man, short and flying to Saha as Fraser-McGurk makes room to slash and misses
Spencer Johnson to Fraser-McGurk, no run, since Fraser-McGurk shuffled across to the off-side, this is not called a wide, fullish and down leg, he goes for the scoop and misses
Spencer Johnson to Fraser-McGurk, FOUR, lucky and four. A back of a length delivery outside off, Fraser-McGurk is going after everything, thick bottom-edge beats short third man to his right
Spencer Johnson to Fraser-McGurk, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Spencer Johnson to Fraser-McGurk, out Caught by Abhinav Manohar!! Good bowling and Fraser-McGurk goes. He makes room outside the leg-stump, Spencer Johnson follows him there with a full ball, no room for Fraser-McGurk as he flicks and finds mid-wicket. Simple catch and respite for GT. Fraser-McGurk c Abhinav Manohar b Spencer Johnson 20(10) [4s-2 6s-2]
Abishek Porel, left handed bat, comes to the crease

Warrier to Prithvi Shaw, no run, another review for LBW taken by Gill. He is getting excited and ignores Saha's advice. Saha can only smile after Gill takes the review. This is a sharp nipbacker but sliding down leg, Prithvi Shaw flicks across the line and misses, easily missing leg and that's a review wasted
Warrier to Prithvi Shaw, FOUR, all wrists. A back of a length delivery around off, whipped over mid-wicket, trademark Prithvi Shaw who picked the length so early
Warrier to Prithvi Shaw, 2 runs, half a chance for caught and bowled! Full on the stumps, chipped back and Warrier can't haul it in, Gill does well to parry it to long-on where Mohit covers up
Warrier to Prithvi Shaw, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Warrier to Prithvi Shaw, out Caught by Spencer Johnson!! What a good short ball and Prithvi Shaw is made to look very ordinary. He is not expecting that, goes down to avoid, but leaves the bat hanging, lobs off there and a dolly to short third man. That was not the right way to play the short ball, Shaw did not go down early nor did he try to drop his hands. Gets out in a clumsy way. Prithvi Shaw c Spencer Johnson b Warrier 7(6) [4s-1]
Shai Hope, right handed bat, comes to the crease

Warrier to Shai Hope, no run, almost another one. The scrambled-seam nipbacker and it just misses off-stump. Shai Hope goes for a big drive on the rise, it nips back in and beats the inside-edge and misses off-stump by not much
Warrier to Shai Hope, no run, short of length on off, tight delivery and easy back foot block
Spencer Johnson to Abishek Porel, 1 run, back of a length outside off, dabbed away to third man and Abishek Porel is away
Spencer Johnson to Shai Hope, 1 run, back of a length into the hips, nudged to deep backward square leg
Spencer Johnson to Abishek Porel, no run, zippy back of a length delivery into the groin, Abishek Porel pulls and misses, is hit on the box and Porel is down and sucking up all the air in, I0$
Porel is down and the physio is out there. Wonder what the physio can say when one is hit on the box. He is up and now ready to go again.
Spencer Johnson to Abishek Porel, no run, back of a length and rising outside off, Abishek Porel tries to cut late and misses
Spencer Johnson to Abishek Porel, wide, short and too short outside off, Abishek Porel on his tiptoes fails to connect and rightly called a wide
Spencer Johnson to Abishek Porel, FOUR, fine shot. On a back of a length just outside off, Abishek Porel punches well as he stands tall and beats point to his left
Spencer Johnson to Abishek Porel, FOUR, short into the body, Abishek Porel swivels nicely and pulls it to the unmanned deep square leg fence
Warrier to Shai Hope, FOUR, wrong line and four more. Full and into the pads, flicked away to the deep square leg fence, so easy

Warrier to Shai Hope, SIX, that has come from nowhere.I0$. Shai Hope comes down the track and flat-bats the back of a length delivery, gets hold of it and it flies all the way over long-on. Totally out of character from Hope but boy did he nail that or what
Warrier to Shai Hope, SIX, six more. Shai Hope is on song. Fullish and on middle, too straight and flicked away over deep square leg, flies into the fence, Warrier smiles wryly
Warrier to Shai Hope, 1 run, full outside off, driven to mid-off and Shai Hope sets off quickly, makes it easily

Warrier to Abishek Porel, SIX, this is a very big over. A short of length delivery on the hips, Abishek Porel swivels and pulls it stylishly over deep backward square leg, the fielder was there but he was just a spectator
Warrier to Abishek Porel, THATS OUT!! Bowled!!

Warrier to Abishek Porel, out Bowled!! Warrier knocks over Abishek Porel. Full on off, Abishek Porel tries to flick too square and misses, has a mock shy with the bat at the stumps in anger as he is disappointed with himself. Not the ball to be playing too square and he pays the price. Warrier does not even bother to celebrate. Abishek Porel b Warrier 15(7) [4s-2 6s-1]

Wonder why there is a delay here? Such a waste of time. It's almost 3 minutes since Abishek Porel fell and the next over has not started yet. The batters are ready, live visuals show Gill setting the field.
Rishabh Pant, left handed bat, comes to the crease
Rashid Khan, right-arm leg break, comes into the attack
Rashid Khan to Shai Hope, 1 run, tossed up googly on middle, flicked through the vacant mid-wicket area
Rashid Khan to Pant, 1 run, the orthodox leggie, good length on the middle and leg line, flicked to deep square leg
Rashid Khan to Shai Hope, no run, quicker and on middle, Shai Hope wants to come forward, then adjusts to push it back, nearly was caught napping there
Rashid Khan to Shai Hope, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Rashid Khan to Shai Hope, out Caught by Mohit Sharma!! Straight to backward point. Was tossed up outside off, Shai Hope reverse-sweeps and hits it well but straight to Mohit at backward point and he makes no mistake. Rashid Khan has a finger-up staring celebration at Hope. Shai Hope c Mohit Sharma b Rashid Khan 19(10) [4s-1 6s-2]
Sumit Kumar, right handed bat, comes to the crease
Rashid Khan to Sumit Kumar, no run, flat back of a length outside off, Sumit Kumar mistimes the cut to point
Rashid Khan to Sumit Kumar, no run, what a beaut! Fizzing legbreak outside off, full and Sumit Kumar pushes in hope with feet stuck in cement, misses
Noor Ahmad, comes into the attack

Noor Ahmad to Pant, no run, slower and tossed up outside off, Pant sweeps and it's a soft top-edge to short fine-leg, Noor Ahmad appeals for an LBW, replays show that it hit the arm and there was no top-edge
Noor Ahmad to Pant, FOUR, too much room outside off, tossed up full outside off, Pant gets forward and flat-bats the drive over the leaping cover, went down very low to get under that
Noor Ahmad to Pant, no run, now he comes down the track but is not to the pitch, so gets the pad in the way, struck outside the line of off, dribbles to cover
Noor Ahmad to Pant, 1 run, fullish outside off, swept to deep square leg for one
Noor Ahmad to Sumit Kumar, leg byes, 1 run, spins back in, but down leg, Sumit Kumar goes on the back foot to whip, misses, impact outside the leg-stump, they take a legbye
Noor Ahmad to Pant, 1 run, flat back of a length outside off, cut wide of backward point
Rashid Khan to Pant, 1 run, back of a length on the stumps, Pant pulls to deep backward square leg
Rashid Khan to Sumit Kumar, 1 run, good length googly and on off, Sumit Kumar makes room to punch to sweeper cover
Rashid Khan to Pant, SIX, just clears long-off. Pant comes down the track and gets enough on the loft to clear the fielder at long-off, off the thick outside half of the bat
Rashid Khan to Pant, 2 runs, Pant gets lucky, gets a fat top-edge on the sweep, Johnson from backward square leg went running back but it falls beyond his reach, was going around in circles there
Rashid Khan round the wicket.
Rashid Khan to Pant, no run, full on the stumps, Pant makes room to loft, thick inside-edge rolls to short fine-leg
Rashid Khan to Pant, no run, flat good length outside off, dabbed straight to the fielder at backward point and sent back by Sumit Kumar
Noor Ahmad to Sumit Kumar, no run, tossed up full outside the leg-stump, a forward defence
Noor Ahmad to Sumit Kumar, FOUR, tries the googly but it's short and wide outside off, thumped away wide of cover
Noor Ahmad to Sumit Kumar, no run, ugly swipe and nearly gone. Was the googly again, just misses the off-stump as Sumit Kumar hacks and misses
Noor Ahmad to Sumit Kumar, no run, flat and quick outside off, Sumit Kumar goes on the back foot to cut and misses
Noor Ahmad to Sumit Kumar, FOUR, game done! Sumit Kumar goes on the back foot to pull, nearly sneaks through but the thick inside-edge runs wide of short fine-leg and goes to the fence

22:14 Local Time, 16:44 GMT, 22:14 IST: What a thrashing this is for GT at home. The batting totally flopped and that was game done almost at the halfway stage. That they managed to take 4 wickets in the chase should be the only solace for them. Fraser-McGurk at the top threatened to finish it off in a jiffy but Johnson got him and Warrier chipped in with a couple of wickets. But DC always had one eye on the NRR and they kept going for it. In the end they finished it off in just 8.5 overs which should boost their NRR massively as well as depleting GT's. An early finish here and a totally unexpected result for GT are a very good side at home. Stay tuned for the presentation...

Shubman Gill | GT skipper: Our batting was very average, and it is important to move on and come back strong. The wicket was alright, if you see some of the dismissals, it had nothing to do with the pitch. Poor shot selection I would say. When the opposition are chasing 89, unless someone takes a double hat-trick, the opposition will always be in the game. This is just the halfway mark of the season for us, we have won 3 and hopefully we win another 5-6 from the next 7 like in the last couple of years.

Jake Fraser-McGurk - Trying to get off to a nice start, try and get the NRR to our favour. When you're riding this wave (of form), you have to try and do it for a long time, cricket is a funny game. We got the better of the conditions, dew came in, the ball skidded on and made batting easier (in the second innings). I didn't play a lot of spin as well. It's pretty surreal, you have to pinch yourself to have played along with him (on Ricky Ponting), I remember in his last Test, Nathan Lyon coming on and talking about it. We have now got the confidence going, started slowly and lost a few matches, but we now have a hang on our own game, I didn't need a second invitation to get going (on being aggressive), that was my natural game.
Four wickets lost inside PP this IPL MI vs RR, Wankhede DC vs KKR, Vizag GT vs DC, Ahmedabad* DC vs GT, Ahmedabad*
Most wickets lost inside PP in IPL 2024 13 - DC* 12 - LSG 11 - RCB 11 - RR 10 - GT

Fewest overs taken to chase 90+ target in IPL (20 overs games) 7.2 - KTK vs RR, Indore, 2011 (Tar: 98) 8.2 - MI vs RR, Sharjah, 2021 (Tar: 91) 8.5 - DC vs GT, Ahmedabad, 2024 (Tar: 90)* 10.0 - KKR vs RCB, Abu Dhabi, 2021 (Tar: 93)
Biggest IPL win for DC in balls remaining 67 vs GT, Ahmedabad, 2024* 57 vs PBKS, Mumbai BS, 2022 42 vs Deccan Chargers, Hyderabad, 2008 40 vs CSK, Delhi, 2012
7th PoTM Award for Rishabh Pant in IPL, only Virender Sehwag (10) have more while playing for Delhi Capitals.
Stats round-up by Shashikant Singh

Rishabh Pant | DC captain and Player of the Match: Lots of things to be pleased about. We talked about the champion thought process and our team showed today that we can play like that and really happy to see that. [on the bowling] Definitely one of the best, it's early on in the tournament, can't say much as we can improve individually. The only thought process before coming on to the field was coming in a better way, that's the only thought when I was going through my rehab. The only conversation we had before the chase was - let's get it as early as possible, we lost a few run-rate points earlier and we covered it up. We just love being in Ahmedabad, we love the stadium, the vibe here and looking forward to play more matches here. We just want to enjoy our win, one at a time and move forward learning from it.

After all the run-glut we saw over the last few days, a low-scoring game and an early finish. The IPL throws up a surprise when you least expect it. On that note, we sign off from here. Till tomorrow, when we come back, take care and be well. Also remember to sleep tight and cuddle well. See you soon.
